values.comments:
This course is designed to explore the unique issues that arise for communications researchers who work with children. The class begins by considering the role of theory in designing research, then reviews the major methodological approaches, and finally examines the variety of contexts in which such research is employed. The course considers the unique ethical issues and protective mechanisms in place. The course culminates in group-based, supervised research wherein students have an opportunity to design and implement a child-focused study. &#8232;
&#8232;Students reported that the course was one of “the most useful and well-taught” they had taken at Penn. Although it “was a good course overall”, some students reported difficulty having no prior research class experience.&#8232;&#8232;
The course was co-taught. Students wrote that Professor Linebarger was “a sweetheart” and a “great teacher,” but many found her “not very organized” overall.&#8232; One student wrote, “I especially enjoyed the balance between [the two] personalities, [they] both complement each other as instructors” while another wrote it “hindered my learning experience…too many conflicting styles of teaching.”
Students said the exams were hard with one student mentioning that material they were tested on was “too trivial.” The course culminated in a final project, which included a significant time of prep-work and execution time.
